         <div type="transcription">
            <p><milestone unit="passage" n="13.7d-13.13c"/>
<lb corresp="#a1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>mā</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a2"/><w><supplied>nān</supplied>y<supplied>e</supplied>ṣ<supplied>āṃ</supplied></w><w>spṛh<supplied>ako</supplied></w><w>bhave<supplied>t</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<w><supplied>ompa</supplied><lb corresp="#a3"/>lskoñe</w><w>mā</w><w>yänmāṣṣäṃ</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="3"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a4"/><w>-tse</w><pc>•</pc><w>ahi</w><w>mūṣakadurgaṃ</w><w>vā</w><pc>•</pc><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a5"/><w>k<supplied>wr</supplied>i</w><pc>•</pc><w>śrā<supplied>maṇyārtheṣv</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<w><supplied>ekadha</supplied><lb corresp="#b1"/>rm<supplied>aṃ</supplied></w><w>c<supplied>a</supplied></w><gap reason="plain" quantity="8"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><w>sāṅghikaṃ</w><w>n<supplied>ā</supplied>v<supplied>a</supplied>m<supplied>a</supplied>ny<supplied>e</supplied>ta</w><pc>•</pc><w>s<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><w>tākaṃ</w><pc>•</pc><w>śīleṣu</w><w>susamā<supplied>h</supplied>it<supplied>aḥ</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><w><supplied>a</supplied>s<supplied>t</supplied>are</w><w>śaul</w><w>ś<supplied>a</supplied>ye<supplied>ñc</supplied>ai</w><w>snai</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b5"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>i</supplied>ti</w><w>jñā<supplied>tvā</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] (one should not be) envious towards others</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] he does not attain concentration</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (attentive to the duties of monkhood) [SKT] like a snake [to] the mouse hole</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] if (one searched for a happy life) [SKT] (attentive to the duties) of monkhood</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] and (one should practise) the only law</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] one should not despise [the garment and the food and drink] of the monks</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] if someone (knows little) [SKT] [but] is practising the morale</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">if he is [someone who] knows little</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>323</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] [who] lives a pure life and is in(defatigable)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] (thinking) that he knows little</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels"><bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>202-204</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:chakravarti1930"/><citedRange>157-160</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:hahn2007"/><citedRange>51</citedRange></bibl></note><note type="remarks">Although the fragments IOL Toch 579 (left, original size w: 3,9 cm, h: 4,4 cm) and IOL Toch 1187 (right, original size w: 3,6 cm, h: 4,4 cm) were edited separately in <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2008a"/><citedRange>100-102</citedRange></bibl>, they clearly belong together. There are no lines missing between a5 and b1, even though the lower margin of the recto (upper of the verso) is not itself preserved. The blank space to the left is probably not the string hole space (pace <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2008a"/><citedRange>100</citedRange></bibl>) because it seems to cover also line a5, which is the last; therefore, the left margin must be preserved. Still, the leaf number is not preserved: perhaps it stood left of lines b4-5.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment"><hi>m[ā]</hi>: The reading is not certain. It could also be <hi>rme</hi> of Uv.13.7d <hi>dharmeṇa na vaṇik caret</hi>. If it is really <hi>mā</hi>, it may be TB <hi>mā</hi> 'not', rendering Skt. <hi>na</hi> of the same line. The TB translation may have been <hi>pelaiknesa mā karyor yāmi</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Uv.13.8b <hi>nānyeṣāṃ spṛhako bhavet</hi>. The akṣara <hi>spṛ</hi> is difficult to read because a tiny piece is flipped over from the verso, see the comment to line b4.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Uv.13.8d <hi>samādhiṃ nādhigacchati</hi>. The following traces, illegible by themselves, must be <hi>[8] (s)[ukh](aṃ)</hi>, the beginning of Uv.13.9a <hi>sukhaṃ jīvitum icchec cet</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Uv.13.9b-c <hi>śrāmaṇyārtheṣv avekṣavān / ahir mūṣakadurgaṃ vā</hi>, here apparently with <hi>ahi</hi> for <hi>ahir</hi>, as no <hi>r</hi> can be read on top of the akṣara <hi>mū</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Uv.13.10a-b <hi>sukhaṃ jīvitum icchec cec chrāmaṇyārtheṣv avekṣavān</hi></note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Uv.13.10d <hi>ekadharmaṃ ca bhāvayet</hi></note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Uv.13.11c <hi>sāṃghikaṃ nāvamanyeta</hi>. The following <hi>[s]·</hi> is the beginning of the TB translation of <hi>sāṃghikaṃ</hi>, possibly <hi>saṅkaṣṣe</hi> v.s.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Uv.13.12a-b <hi>alpajñāto ’pi ced bhavati śīleṣu susamāhitaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment"><hi>śīle[ṣ]u</hi>: the <hi>ś</hi> is closed at the bottom and looks a bit like <hi><hi rend="underline">s</hi></hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Uv.13.12d <hi>śuddhājīvam atandritam</hi></note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment"><hi>(a)s(t)are śaul</hi>: <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht31"/> a5 reads <hi>āstreṃ śaul</hi>, a verse variant of regular prose <hi>astare</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment"><hi>śau<hi rend="underline">l</hi> [ś]·[y]e·ai</hi>: the reading <hi><hi rend="underline">l</hi> [ś]·</hi> is problematic because the <hi>ś</hi> seems to be attached directly below the <hi><hi rend="underline">l</hi></hi>. If <hi>śaul śayeñcai</hi> was written together, one would at all times expect an akṣara <hi>lśa</hi>, not <hi><hi rend="underline">l</hi>śa</hi>. Probably, the scribe mixed up the two possible spellings <hi>lśa</hi> in one akṣara and <hi><hi rend="underline">l</hi><hi rend="subscript">\</hi> śa</hi> in two akṣaras. The <hi>ś</hi> is partly readable in the reconstructed image, but part of it was flipped over to the recto (see the comment to line a2) on the original image.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">Uv.13.13c <hi>alpajñātam iti jñātvā</hi></note></p>
         </div>
